            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nThis text introduces the idea of subtraction, one of the four fundamental operations. To do this, we will use the knowledge covered in the six previous chapters of the *First Steps* of *History Tracers* (<htcite0>). We suggest studying them before proceeding.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b5efc8f9-c268-430f-9681-7a43848ee48e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "First Steps",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nIn the previous text, we observed that when performing division, there can be remainders. From this, we concluded that there is a need for a special operation to perform this measurement. Another important point observed was that as we move away from a number that is a multiple—that is, whose division has no remainder—the remainders increase until they finally return to zero at the next multiple in the multiplication table (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "5a0fcf99-1d9b-43df-a9b4-03246dd79ae1",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Is this extra?",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: So close, yet so far</b><br /><br />Numbers grow when we move away and shrink when we get closer—this gives us the idea of distance.<br /><br />Could we interpret subtraction as a way of measuring distance in relation to something?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_addition",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Walking\n\nLet's begin by observing Figure 1, which shows paths within the archaeological site of Caral in Peru (*Abya Yala*) (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3b18a263-71e9-4c61-a7fe-c23cbce65624",
                     "text": "Zona Caral",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2023",
                        "month": "9",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"CaralH1\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('CaralH1', '0%')\" src=\"images/Caral/CaralPiramideH1.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 1</b>: Photograph of the H1 pyramid at the Caral archaeological site. Photo taken on <htdate0>, during a visit to the location.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2017",
                     "month": "5",
                     "day": "31"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Now, let's represent one of the paths as a straight line, placing the number zero at the start and the number nine at the end:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3b18a263-71e9-4c61-a7fe-c23cbce65624",
                     "text": "Zona Caral",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2023",
                        "month": "9",
                        "day": "28"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><svg width=\"420\" height=\"100\"  fill=\"none\" stroke=\"black\"> <defs> <marker id=\"arrow\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto-start-reverse\"> <path d=\"M 0 0 L 10 5 L 0 10 z\" /></marker> </defs> <line x1=\"2\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"400\" y2=\"15\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow)\" /> <text x=\"0\" y=\"40\" font-size=\"1.5em\">0</text> <text x=\"40\" y=\"40\" font-size=\"1.5em\">1</text> <text x=\"80\" y=\"40\" font-size=\"1.5em\">2</text> <text x=\"120\" y=\"40\" font-size=\"1.5em\">3</text> <text x=\"160\" y=\"40\" font-size=\"1.5em\">4</text> <text x=\"200\" y=\"40\" font-size=\"1.5em\">5</text> <text x=\"240\" y=\"40\" font-size=\"1.5em\">6</text> <text x=\"280\" y=\"40\" font-size=\"1.5em\">7</text> <text x=\"320\" y=\"40\" font-size=\"1.5em\">8</text> <text x=\"360\" y=\"40\" font-size=\"1.5em\">9</text> <line x1=\"5\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"5\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"45\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"45\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"85\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"85\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"125\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"125\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"165\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"165\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"205\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"205\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"245\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"245\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"285\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"285\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"325\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"325\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" /> <line x1=\"365\" y1=\"15\" x2=\"365\" y2=\"25\" stroke=\"black\" stroke-width=\"3\" />  </svg></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Chart 1</b>: Representation of a path.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### How many steps did I take?\n\nLet's assume that each number shown on the chart represents a step taken while walking. Therefore, upon reaching position 9, it means we have taken 9 steps in total.\n\nIn previous texts, we learned to write this result in different ways, as shown in **Table 1**:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"emptyGrid\" class=\"tableTen\"> <tr><td style=\"background-color: lightblue\">Text</td><td style=\"background-color: lightblue\"><b>Adding</b></td><td style=\"background-color: lightblue\"><b>Multiplying</b></td></tr>  <tr><td style=\"background-color: white\">Taking one step at a time, we have 9 steps in total.</td><td style=\"background-color: white\">1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 = 9</td><td style=\"background-color: white\">9 × 1 = 9</td></tr> </table></p> <p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Representation of steps using mathematics.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### A New Question\n\nLet's disregard the first step we took and count only the steps starting from position 1.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: From 1 to 9 I have...</b><br /><br />When counting one less step, what happens to the values in <b>Table 1</b>?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"emptyGrid\" class=\"tableTen\"> <tr><td style=\"background-color: lightblue\">Text</td><td style=\"background-color: lightblue\"><b>Adding</b></td><td style=\"background-color: lightblue\"><b>Multiplying</b></td></tr>  <tr><td style=\"background-color: white\">Taking one step at a time, starting from step 1, we have a total of 8 steps.</td><td style=\"background-color: white\">1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 + 1 = 8</td><td style=\"background-color: white\">8 × 1 = 8</td></tr> </table></p> <p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 2</b>: Representation of steps using mathematics.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Counting one less step, we have a total of 8 steps.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_new",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### A New Operation\n\nInstead of recounting the steps, as we did between **Tables 1 and 2**, there is a way to get the result. For this, we use the operation of subtraction, which is defined as (<htcite0>):",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ad7733f8-38ad-406f-abee-d259e45bf383",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Subtração",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><ul class=\"citation\"><li><i>\"Subtraction is the operation of taking the difference (d), where <i>d = x - y</i> of two numbers x and y.\"</i></li> </ul></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Measuring the Distance\n\nAccording to this definition, we can rework the examples from the tables by defining the total path length as **x = 9** for both.\n\nFor **Table 1**, we will define the second value as **y = 0** and, as a consequence, we have:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;9<br />-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;0<br />____________<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;9</center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 1</b>: Number of steps from the origin.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "From **Calculation 1**, we can understand that, starting from the zero position, after taking 9 steps, we will be 9 steps away from the origin.\n\nContinuing our study, let's look at the case of **Table 2**.\n\nIn this scenario, we have the value **y = 1** and, as a consequence:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;9<br />-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;1<br />____________<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;8</center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 2</b>: Number of steps from when we took the first step.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 3: How close am I</b><br /><br />What do <b>Calculations 1 and 2</b> tell us about the origin?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Since we have different results, but always calculated from the last step taken, we can conclude that:\n- The more steps we take, the farther we are from the origin;\n- When we measure distances from closer positions (like after the first step), we get smaller distances;\n- The fact that we measure the distance from a closer position does not make the total path disappear—it still exists, we just stop considering it.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_lost",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Conserving Matter\n\nSubtraction is also associated with losses, reductions, or the act of no longer having something. This feeling or sensation is not wrong, but there is something more behind it—and this is what we will focus on, as this aspect is often forgotten.\n\nLet's look at some scenarios where subtraction occurs:\n- When we eat something, we no longer have the fruit as it originally came to us. On the other hand, it is transformed so that we can obtain energy;\n- When we throw something away, it is no longer present. However, it can be recycled and reused;\n- The most painful case: when someone passes away, they are no longer present as a person, but the atoms that made up that individual are not destroyed. Thus, in due proportion, the matter will still be present.\n\nFrom the simplest to the most complex scenarios, we can understand the feeling of loss as matter in motion, and therefore, being conserved (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\nLet's consider one more example to solidify the concept.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "68227419-2430-4359-b902-f6cf87b8941d",
                     "text": "Holmes, F. L.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "1985",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b9866acb-fde8-4fcb-b54d-ee7c481cc9e7",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Shared Origin",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2010",
                     "month": "",
                     "day": ""
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "unix",
                     "year": "",
                     "month": "",
                     "day": ""
                  },
                  {
                     "type": "julian",
                     "year": "",
                     "month": "",
                     "day": ""
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"> <img id=\"img0\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img0', '0%')\" src=\"images/SanJoseCRMuseo/MusicCR.jpg\" class=\"imgcenter\" /><b>Figure 2</b>: Musical instruments present in Costa Rica (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('3e4dc8f8-8c2b-491e-9e2b-0b3adb927c70'); return false;\">Museo Nacional de Costa Rica</a>). Photo taken during a visit to the museum on <htdate0></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2017",
                     "month": "10",
                     "day": "17"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "In this image, we observe woodwind instruments with a mouthpiece at the top and a perforated shell at the bottom.",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "**Figure 2** shows eight musical instruments present at the National Museum of Costa Rica. Suppose that for one week, four of these objects are moved to another museum so that other people can see them alongside other exhibited pieces. This means that during that week, we will have only four pieces on display in the original museum:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p style=\"text-align=center\"><center>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;8<br />-&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;4<br />____________<br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;4</center></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 3</b>: Representation of the movement of pieces between museums.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In this example, we see that although the pieces are momentarily no longer present, they have not ceased to exist—they were merely moved.\n\nFinally, we draw attention to the relationship between subtraction, addition, and **Chart 1**. When we add numbers, we move forward in the direction of the arrow on the graph, as we saw in different texts in the *First Steps* section (<htcite0>). Now, when we subtract, we move backward or remain at the same point on the graph, depending on the number we subtract.\n\nGiven this scenario, we can understand subtraction as the inverse of addition (<htcite1>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "b5efc8f9-c268-430f-9681-7a43848ee48e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "First Steps",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ad7733f8-38ad-406f-abee-d259e45bf383",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Subtraction",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_conclusion",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Conclusion\n\nIn this text, we learned that subtraction can be understood as a concept of movement, regardless of the context in which we use it.\n\nWe also saw that subtraction is related to addition, being its inverse operation (<htcite0>).\n\nIn the next texts, we will see how to use subtraction together with the other operations we have already studied.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "ad7733f8-38ad-406f-abee-d259e45bf383",
                     "text": "Weisstein, Eric W.",
                     "page": "Subtração",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
   ],
   "exercise_v2": [
      {
         "question": "When measuring distance through subtraction, do we subtract the initial position from the final position?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "Yes",
         "additionalInfo": "Distance tells us how far we have moved, regardless of the means used (on foot, by bicycle, by train, by boat, or by airplane).<br />To do this, we subtract the initial position from the final position:<br />distance = final position − initial position."
      },
      {
         "question": "Are subtraction as movement and subtraction as loss completely different ideas?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "No",
         "additionalInfo": "Even in situations where we consider that something has been lost, there is transformation and movement of matter. Therefore, in both cases, we can interpret subtraction as a form of change or displacement."
      }
   ],
   "game_v2": null,
   "date_time": null
}
